deck_name: Deck Profile from Over the Rainbow
deck_excerpt: Somewhere over the Rainbow... there's a Dragon that is the bridge to other dimensions.
deck_description:
Thanks to the new Structure Deck, known as Legend of the Crystal Beasts, there are many ways to bring forth the seven... wait a minute, there are eight now.  OK, if you want to bring out all the Crystal Beasts to summon an "Ultimate Crystal" monster, this Deck has many new cards to do so.

The fastest way to summon an "Ultimate Crystal" monster (namely, "Rainbow Overdragon") is "Ultimate Crystal Magic", which can activate immediately if you ram one of your monsters into a stronger one and deliberately destroy it.  After that, you can Tribute the Fusion Summoned "Rainbow Overdragon" and summon "Ultimate Crystal Rainbow Dragon Overdrive".  If your opponent has no counter, this will most likely end as a One Turn Kill.

If you want to watch your opponent squirm and stall for time, "Ancient City - Rainbow Ruins" provides a plethora of effects, depending on the number of Crystal Beasts in your Spell & Trap Zones, while "Advanced Dark" allows you to prevent Battle Damage as long as you can send a Crystal Beast from your Deck to the Graveyard.  For those who wish to use "Rainbow Ruins", "Crystal Tree" will help immensely, but try to limit your Crystal Counters to 2 or less.

"Awakening of the Crystal Ultimates" will definitely aid you in bringing out your key cards, be it a "Rainbow Bridge" card or "Rainbow Refraction", or a "Crystal Beast" monster.  "Ruby Carbuncle" and "Sapphire Pegasus" will benefit the most from these.  Also, "Rainbow Bridge of the Heart" and "Rainbow Bridge of Salvation" are the best "Rainbow Bridge" candidates to draw with that Quick-Play Spell's effect.

Now that you know the basics, give this Deck a workout and see where it gets you.  And as always, keep smiling, and keep dreaming.

deck_excerpt: Lockdown the board and beat over your opponent with a Mechanized Army in Masterduel!
deck_description:
With the new Masterduel October Banlist , key floodgates like Skill Drain, Rivalry of Warlords and Gozen Match have all been brought down to 2. Pot of Prosperity is also at one. This may have slightly weakened Machina, but Machina will always adapt to the meta!

Excellent support for the archetype includes Machina Citadel, which functions as a quick effect board wipe of all your opponent’s monsters which is a very potent form of interruption. Machina Overdrive enables a circular resource loop between the banished pile, GY, deck and hand, while Machina Redeployment greatly increased the consistency of the deck. Newer support from main sets like Unclaspare (R4NK enabler, free special summon and foolish burial) and Ruinforce (4600ATK beatstick and banish recursion) have also greatly increased the power for this archetype.

The resulting support turns Machina from an archetype that was a jumbled mess into a compact powerful fighting force that can succeed in a grind game. Together with high impact staple trap cards and crippling floodgates, Machina functions as an anti-meta deck versus the combo-heavy meta! Control the game, simplify the game-state, then OTK your opponent in one fell swoop with your high ATK Machina army!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Why am I not running The Monarchs Erupt? The card is nowhere near as good as you think it is. "But mah skill drains", playing six skill drains is actually bad. Skill drain is a great card, but at six it is useless, and drawing into multiple copies sucks, not to mention you're less likely to be able to get a monster on the field rendering Erupt useless. Erupt also conflicts with Anchamoufrite after Pot of Duality has been activated, and I can 100% promise you 3x anchamoufrite is more valuable that 3x a brick.

Erupt being an assymetrical floodgate actually isn't that big of a deal given the fact that every monster in your deck can tribute your skill drain if it becomes obsolete and you'd rather have the search. Please just stop running Erupt unless it's for budget reasons, because that is the only valid reason to play it over skill drain.

Evil Eye is absolutely fantastic with the new support. It can put up multiple interruptions from a single card as well as huge towers. The new support completely changes the deck and makes it far better than it was previously. This build doesn't play Pot of Prosperity intentionally for budget reasons, but if you own a playset or are able to afford it, it is fantastic in this deck. The other thing to consider is a small kshatri-la package (3x Kshatri-La Fenrir and 1x Kshatri-La Berth). The kshatri-la package is great, it's a free searchable banish that also serves as material for your D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex plays and can help you extend into your links, but it will most likely cost a fortune and thus isn't fit for a budget build. Furthermore, it isn't essential, and is just a nice addition to an already complete deck.

Top priority is getting Serziel, Watcher of the Evil Eye out, you can do this with either Evil Eye Domain - Pareidolia, Terraforming (to search Pareidolia) or Evil Eye Retribution. However, through the retribution method (send serziel + Basiltrice, Familiar of the Evil Eye, add Evil Eye Awakening then activate it to ss Serziel) you do not get his search effect, but you can still extend into Gorgon, Empress of the Evil Eyed by then activating Basiltrice from the GY, the usefulness of this play is predicated on you having either another searcher for Evil Eye of Selene or Selene itself in your hand. After normal summoning serziel, send Evil Eye of Gorgoneio and Basiltrice to search Selene, chain Basiltrice in the GY to special summon it, then banish Gorgoneio and discard Selene to search either Evil Eye Retribution, Evil Eye Defeat or Gorgoneio. Make Gorgon, chain retribution in the GY to equip Selene to Gorgon, then set all your interruptions/equip gorgoneio. If you had a Basilius, Familiar of the Evil Eye in hand, or an uneeded Pareidolia to search for one, you should make Gorgon without Basiltrice so that you can gain an additional interruption off of Basilius's quick effect that allows you to link summon on your opponents turn. Usually you make Zerrziel, Ruler of the Evil Eyed off of this.

Be careful with how many equip spells you use. Although it is very fun to make a 20k+ Zerrziel, you're just going to burn yourself to death (this is bad). You do not need a 20k zerziell that can attack twice, and ultimately you're just weakening your position by spamming equip spells on a single target with a compulsory effect.

deck_description:
A 'Dissolverock' Deck for Yugi/Kaiba format (May 2002). Best deck in the format.

Aren't you tired of losing to your opponent's Trap Holes? Dissolverock is the answer, The highest ATK of a monster that still can't be destroyed by Trap Hole. Technically tied for the highest but with all the Dissolverock support cards able to boost its ATK once it's on the field it's definitely the best choice. A word of caution though, if you already have Wasteland on the field then Dissolverock can be destroyed by Trap Hole so remember to use your De-Spell then summon Dissolverock then activate your second Wasteland. deck_excerpt: Updated version, new Odd-Eyes XYZ and banlist compliant
deck_description:
What's new for this deck? First, the "The Newborn Dragon" selection box added Odd-Eyes Rebellion Dragon Overlord which this deck can make in niche situations, and second, the september 30th banlist banned Crystron Halqifibrax which I was running in Gaia for the Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians into Effect Veiler into Accesscode Talker that every OTK deck used at the time, and also eased the restrictions on going second cards like Raigeki and Dinowrestler Pankratops which are both specially good in this deck (Raigeki is a great replacement for Lightning Storm which in our deck would often be dead thanks to our use of field spells, while Pankratops can be used for rank 7 XYZ plays )

The main combo of this deck is: summon Gaia the Magical Knight, summon Curse of Dragon, the Cursed Dragon via Magical Knight's effect, search Spiral Fusion with Cursed Dragon's effect and finally fusion summon whichever Gaia fusion you need; if you already have access to Spiral Fusion, you should search Spiral Reborn instead. To make this combo more consistent we run several consistency tools: both Artillery Catapult Turtle and Galloping Gaia can search both Magical Knight and Cursed Dragon, while Gateway to Chaos can only search Magical Knight.

deck_excerpt: "When there is an opportunity, Cease it"
deck_description:
New format means new opportunities for the already trench diseased metagame. New players step up, while former contenders step down or get neutered; current contendors that were rogue either become the new key players, or get sacked from their position; or the king of kings from last format retain their throne until the next banlist. Dinosaurs this format are in the best of both worlds in this situation. Sure they didn't get their key cards back nor the True King engine (Excluding Calamities) hasn't came back; but that honestly hasn't stopped them from being at least playable. At least if you are willing to seethe and cope for another 3-5 months with a awkward, wobbly, and fragile rhythm of building up to until you get to Ultimate Conductor Tyranno.

 

  However rest assured it didn't take as long as expected to figure this out (maybe about 3 days, but that's better than what most take to figure out how to make Burn decks competitive without Mystic Mine). For one Twitter has done the only good thing (before Elon Musk came in), and insist to make a small Spright package be inserted into the Dino War Machine. That in the end has payed off very well, and allowed not only the recycling of Babycerasaurus; but also allow for further extensions, and access to the Rank-2 monster "Number 45: Crumble Logos the Prophet of Demolition" (read the card text, then look at why I also added Infinite Impermanence in the deck as well). While Crystron Halqifibrax is no longer in circulation as the synchro fodder; it didn't stop LV8 Synchro monsters like "Blood Melfist" and "Borreload Savage Dragon" from being played, thanks to the PSY-Framegear package widely available (and more accessable with PSY-Framelord Lambda). 

 

  Finally comes the original Dino lineup, which has hit multiple times on the banlist throughout the years; but still manage to opportunisticaly comeback to competitive sphere at any given moment. Even with Miscellaneousaurus still being at 1 copy per deck, banishing with Giant Rex can make a Rank-4 monster in one turn (if Souleating Oviraptor is on the field at the time). Not to mention that Babycerasaurus is still unlimited, which not only gives a reason to play the mentioned "Spright" package from earlier; but also gives fuel for Ultimate Conductor Tyranno, and gives you options to go into Rank-2 plays. Knightmare Unicorn and Accesscode Talker still remain prominent in Dinosaurs to this day, all because of their easy setup; and while not always needed, can be used at any situation (and can give you some payment for the cost of Pot of Prosperity).

deck_excerpt: Set up a bunch of disruption alongside White Zoa and either a fully loaded Bayonet punisher or Utopic Future for an assault.
deck_description:
This deck is built to turbo out a White Zoa and up to 4 borrel monsters into your gy in a single turn, but can also use the Bystial engine to make Utopia beyond for a possible OTK, both backed with several hand traps and negates. Note that apparently the Borrelsword/Tetrahertz thing didn't work so I removed it from the deck. This deck works on tearing the bigger picture up rather than preventing it from being painted, and once done, keeps your opponent locked down with negates. Reason being, decks like Tearlaments will continue to do their plays reguardless of how many times you try to negate their effects, so the best way to deal with them is to assert dominance over their prime board.

 

What you do with this deck is start of by dumping Borrels for bayonet punisher(via Nadir servant, Maximus, Dogmatika punishment, and Dogmatikatrix), and removing threats with sphere mode and Ultimate Slayer before ritual summoning Zoa(pieces can be searched by Ecclesia, Dogmatikatrix, and Herald of the arc light)to finish taking threats out. Then, you can safely set your backrow and play your Bystial/Ecclesia cards. And once the board is broken, you use cards like solemn Judgment, Dogmatika Punishment, Ash blossom, and Effect veiler to keep it broken. A thing to keep in mind is that Zoa is an acceptable casualty due to the fact that you have Cyber Eltanin in the deck, who can wipe all monsters off the board so you can land a finishing blow.

 

The bystial work by summoning Magnamuht during your opponent's turn, which adds Druisworm during the end phase. You can summon Druisworm during the end phase. Then, come your turn, overlay both for Utopia beyond, clearing the threat of any beatsticks. And if you didn't OTK with it, White Zoa, and a 3rd monster, then you can overlay it for Zeus. Also, Cyber Eltanin was just added to the list, If Zeus winds up in the gy(which can be done via Dogmatika effects), you can banish it to summon the card, which then sends all monsters on the field to the gy. Paired with lightning storm, this card gives you a clear shot for game.

 

A strong point to this deck is it evades a crazy amount of commonly used staples and floodgates as it avoids being dependent on many vore mechanics a deck can utilize, the list being:

•Secret Village of the spellcasters

•Dimension shifter/Silent graveyard/Marcos cosmos/Dimensional Fissure/D.D. Crow/Artifact Lancea

•Lava golem(In the instance you only have Zoa/Fenrir and a heavy backrow set)

•Winged dragon of ra- Sphere mode

•Extra deck nuisances like Zeus and Bagooska

• Skill drain as Zoa is a beatstick and you have removal

•Iblee

•Kshatria Fenrir as you have several ways around it becoming a threat

•Extra deck based cards such as Dimension barrier and artifact scythe

•There are quite a few instances where Ash Blossom doesn't do anything as you can get your searches another way.

•Zombie World

The big threats to this deck are There can be only one(in the instance you have to search Zoa with Ecclesia), Mystic mine(In the instance that you don't draw one of the 8 removal cards/prosperity). And other cards that prevent you from special summoning are threats.

 

Another strong point to this deck is it's layers of protection. You've got Dogmatika nation which pops anything attacking your Dogmatika monsters so your opponent can't gain a big advantage from wiping your field, White Zoa makes Dogmatika cards unaffected by extra deck monsters like Ghoti mass banishing and can't be bullied by Tearlaments stealing your turn, and you have Wind pegasus, which shuffles a threat away if said threat destroys a card. And if you added it in, Palladium Oracle Mana protects your Dogmatika monsters from being targeted or destroyed by card effects.

Things you can play but I didn't include are:

Dark Ruler No more instead of Ultimate Slayer to save yourself $130.

Cyber emergency to search Eltanin.

2/3Magicians' souls and 1 Palladium Oracle Mana for an extra layer of protection on your Dogmatika monsters and extra draw power. Oracle Mana presents your opponent from targeting and destroying your level 7 or higher spellcasters, AKA Zoa/Maximus/Flueridis.

Prosperity can come in handy, but isn't an absolute must have for the deck. You can use an Upstart goblin, one day of peace, and an Into the void instead if you want to save a ton. You could also go with wonder wand on Ecclesia or a Maximus that has served it's purpose(probably the better option of the two cheaper methods, but prosperity is still the best option).

Update: I put Link disciple in the side deck in case you end up facing a Spright player using Knightmare Corruptor Iblee, you can link it away and continue comboing. Dragonmaid Lorpar replaced Bhalyutia the grand radiance in the side deck, either can be used but I prefer Lorpar for it's ability to force out negates and force Zeus to activate it's effect before you set up with Ecclesia or Dogmatikatrix.

Thats all I have on this deck for now, but I might update it sometime later if I stumble across better tech options.
WIP

deck_excerpt: Unchained Core with a Tour Guide Splash.
deck_description:
[This list is for the 10/03/22 banlist format before the release of Darkwing Blast]. I expect the top decks in this format to remain relatively unchanged with Tearlament being the prominent deck and Spright still being tier 2. Other top decks will most likely be Drytron, Despai, Stun, Exosister, and Mathmech/cyberse. Matches are often going into time as a combination of long turns and grindier matches cause individual games to go as long as 30 minutes.

1) D.D. Crow, Ghost belle & Haunted Mansion, and Infinite Impermanence are some of the best hand traps currently. This is because they can all end can Tearlament's turn on their own depending on the opponent's hand and mills. D.D. crow is the premier hand trap in this format and can also shut down our own turn if our opponent happens to banish Sarama's target or one of our best resource engines in Disaster. Ghost Belle doubles as a defensive tool to negate D.D. crow incase our opponent tries that. Due to the recent banning of Ronin Toadin, Spright is now also weak to Ghost belle as they need to specifically special summon Swap Frog from the GY with Spright Elf in order to go into Toadally Awesome.

2)  Tour Guide From the Underworld: Because games are slower, having access to both Dark Spirits means we are favored in any grind game. Tour guide can either tutor both dark spirits from the deck by linking into Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss or search Sangan to either grab a hand trap or an unchained monster for follow-up.

3)  Rivalry of Warlords is one of the best flood gates in the current meta. A well timed activation can skip your opponents entire turn and also has the benefit of slowing the pace of the game to a speed where Unchained fares better. (edited)

4) The extra deck is pretty boilerplate. It's worth noting that Tour Guide does allow easier access to Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder making him viable in this deck when you go 2nd.

5) As far as the side deck goes, I have floodgates, extra hand traps, and a few board breakers. Anti-spell Fragrance goes in when I have to go first against anything except Spright. Solemn judgement will make sure it sticks. For weird match-ups where Rivalry is not relevant, there are extra hand traps. Including Ghost Mourner & Moonlit Chill. As I mentioned earlier, matches are often going into time. Ghost mourner can force your opponent to stop playing otherwise they have the potential of losing in time. It also doubles as another copy of Infinite Impermanence whereas Ghost Sister & Spooky Dogwood is completely useless otherwise.

Dark Ruler No More is unfortunately a necessary evil until Spright all but drops from the meta. It’s a 1 card win con in the match up but doesn’t pair very well against the other top decks.

If you find it interesting, please give me a subscrice chanel
hehehe ahaha
Ye

The strategy that im using its trying to summon the Rainbow Overdragon (R.O) (always treated as an ultimate crystal) ASAP, ive seen that most decks try to summon him in an slow way or they try to play Conclave control, and thats to slow for me, so what we are gonna do its focusing on the Ultimate Crystal Magic this Trap Card its gonna get us the summon of the "R.O" so easy, we just need that our opponent attack us and destroy us one crystal beast (can be set face down or face up) and thats gonna trigger the effect of send 7 crystal beast with different names from our hand, field or deck to the GY and we  can special summon one "Ultimate Crystal" Fussion monster from our extra deck (and it treated as a Fussion Summon; This is important because for the next summon we need to banish from our gy or field one fussion summoned "Ultimate Crystal".  So once we summon our R.O we have two choises, keep it on the field protecting us or we can use his quick effect by tributing this fussion summoned card and send all the cards on the field back to the decks, then we can just wait to the opponet to end his turn. Now because we summon in a duel  an Ultimate Crystal Monster and because we have 7 crystal beast and the "R.O" in our GY we can special summon our "Ultimate Crystal Rainbow Dragon Overdrive" and he gains 7k attack so he will have 11k, and also he can as quick effect if he hasnt attacked in the turn tribute himself and send all the cards from the field back to the deck and summoning back any number of the banished crystal beast monsters. also between this two summonigs we can summon the "Rainbow Dragon"  i recomend to summon him after you use the R.O quick effect, so you will have him and the "Ultimate Crystal Rainbow Overdrive" in the field too. And that's it, this deck have worked very good for me so far, its fun to play and quick but we have to be very careful with not getting any of the single crystal beast killed or banished cuz we need 7 different beast in our hand, deck or field, so be careful with that and use the ones that have extra copies most of the time. Protect your "Ultimate Crystal Magic" at all cost haha because with out that your gonna be playing the slow way, you could still do the main combo but it will take you more time and will be harder.  So thats it, have fun playing my deck.

deck_excerpt: Those useless Lvl 5 Water monsters? They're back and they're...slightly less useless...
deck_description:
Use A Legendary Ocean to lower the level of all Water monsters in the hand/on the field and then summon the (former) level 5 (now level 4) Water monsters from your hand without needing a tribute.

The important thing is to get A Legendary Ocean on the field and then start summoning. The cards listed here are some of the classic level 5 Water monsters from the earlier days of Yu-Gi-Oh! I though it would be fun to use them since they were never particularly good and now there is a way to play them (relatively) easily.

Any level 5 Water monsters can be used and I added some other possibilities to the side deck.

The extra deck is mainly rank 4 Xyz monsters that can be used since A Legendary Ocean lowers the level of all Water monsters in the hand and on the field. I only put Water monsters in the Extra deck, but there are other rank 4 Xyz options as well as other Link and Synchro monsters that could be used (just make sure you add some Tuners to the Main deck).

You could use level 4 and lower cards such as Mother Grizzly to special summon Catapult Turtle or any other Water monster with <1500 ATK or you could use  Buzzsaw Shark (with more Fish type monsters in the deck) and use it to summon additional monsters to the field (along with being able to use it for rank 3-5 Xyz monsters).

There are likely other monsters/archetypes that would work well with this kind of deck so experiment and have fun with it!

deck_excerpt: Only card better than Exodia is Mystic Mine no cap
deck_description:
This is based on the 2018 Treasure Panda Exodia FTK by Daniel Ramirez made with adjustments for forbidden list changes since then. Shoutout to AznEyesWhiteDragon on YouTube for posting the decklist.

 

Optimal Combo:

1) summoner monk -> special summon treasure panda from deck.

 

2) Use whatever spells you have in hand that are able to be activated to put at least 3 spells in the GY.

 

3) Treasure Panda -> banish any ONE random spell (besides Primal Seed) to special summon Flamvell Guard.

 

4) Synchro summon using Flamvell Guard and Summoner Monk into T.G. Hyper Librarian.

 

5) Use Treasure Panda's effect twice more to get an Exodia piece and Flamvell Guard or Water Spirit.

 

6) Synchro Summon using that Exodia piece and Flamvell Guard or Water Spirit into Formula Synchron.

 

7) Use the effects of T.G. Hyper Librarian and Formula Synchron to draw a card from each card's effect.

 

8) Repeat steps 5-7 until Treasure Panda's effect can't be used anymore.

 

You should have T.G. Hyper Librarian, Formula Synchron, Treasure Panda, and a second Formula Synchron.

 

9) Synchro summon using Treasure Panda and one of the Formula Synchrons into Stardust Charge Warrior.

 

10) Use T.G. Hyper Librarian and Stardust Charge Warrior's effects to draw a card. 

 

From here, the combo can branch out into multiple routes depending on what other cards were in your starting hand. BUT, every route you attempt from Step 10 MUST end with all of these conditions fulfilled;

 

All 4 normal monster pieces of Exodia must be banished (the most optimal way to get this requirement is by using Soul Release on every Exodia piece in the GY)

At least 2 copies of Primal Seed must be in your hand (the most optimal way to get this requirement is by draw power)

Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning must be in one of your monster zones. (you must do step 9 before completing this requirement) 

The head of Exodia must be in your hand. (complete this requirement with draw power)

 

11) Use Primal Seed to bring back two of the banished Exodia pieces.

 

12) Repeat Step 11.

 

If you have done it right, you will have won on the first turn of the duel. Good luck to you all and Long Live Exodia!!!!

deck_excerpt: Negates. Opponent's turn board clears. Mystic Mine outs.
deck_description:
Deck inspired by Trif, but with my own spin on it. The deck is pretty beefy at 45 cards but I don't think I've bricked on more than a handful of occassions. Definitely stronger going first, but there is good support for going second in the sideboard, (of which I'm still trying to lock down if you have suggestions).

Main strategies:

-Create a clear board on opponents turn by creating Spright Elf and I:P Masquerena. Activate Spright Elf and search out the Merrli you used, then chain I:P Masquerena to link climb to Topologic Bomber Dragon. Spright Elf resolves and put Merrli to any place the Bomber Dragon is pointing to, this of course triggers Merrli's summon AND grave effect. Topologic Bomber Dragon is NOT once per turn.

-Create a board of negates with Baronne de Fleur which you can get out fairly easily using your Scareclaw package. Predaplant Dragostapelia, and Wandering Gryphon Rider. (Just make sure you didn't do any normal summons that you activated the effects of, like Merrli or you won't be able to play Rite of Aramesir)

-It is entirely possible to achieve both main strategies, in which case you would try to negate through the board before finally doing your Topologic play as this clears your board as well. If you find this situation coming up often, changing Bomber to Zeroboros would not be a terrible idea.

-Abyss Dweller is there for the mirror matchup and any other decks that benefit from graveyard effects.

-Set rotation for clearing out Mystic Mine

-Mystic Mine for when the match goes sideways and you need a moment to breathe

 

-When siding, consider removing any spell that isn't searchable for your tech choices. 

 

Please let me know what you think! This is the first deck I've submitted and would love feedback.

This deck aims to use the Spright cards in combination with the Trickstar cards in order to create advantage and decent boards without Toadally Awesome

I am using a Trickstar package of 1 Corobane, 3 Candina, 2 Lilybell, 3 Light Stage and 3 Reincarnation. Corobane and Lilybell are extenders, Lilybell is prefered as it's level 2 but Corobane is a free card on the field and can still go into Spright Elf/Sprind. Candina is a normal summon that's not the Nimble cards which searches the field spell which becomes an extender. I am using 3 Dimension Shifter in the main deck as Spright without Toadally Awesome is even less reliant on the graveyard meaning Spright has even more reaso to play Dimension Shifter

I am using 3 Neko Mane King in the side deck as a mill target against Ishizu Tear. If milled, your opponents turn enters the end phase, cutting their turn short.

I am running Cyber-Stein in the side deck as well as a Sprind target to go into DPE for a small sum of 5000 life points.

deck_description:
<!-- [if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><!-- [if gte mso 9]> Normal 0 false false false EN-US X-NONE X-NONE <![endif]--><!-- [if gte mso 9]> <![endif]--><!-- [if gte mso 10]> /* Style Definitions */ table.MsoNormalTable {mso-style-name:"Table Normal"; mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; mso-style-noshow:yes; mso-style-priority:99; mso-style-parent:""; mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt; mso-para-margin-top:0in; mso-para-margin-right:0in; mso-para-margin-bottom:8.0pt; mso-para-margin-left:0in; line-height:107%; mso-pagination:widow-orphan; font-size:11.0pt; font-family:"Calibri",sans-serif; mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"; mso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}<![endif]-->

I created an up to date version of one of my favourite decks of all time, Generaider Windwitch!

If you want a detailed explanation how to use this deck, click here.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!



This deck features incredibly potent anti-meta cards like Dimension Shifter, Macro Cosmos, Imperial Order and True King of Calamities. Generaider Windwitch plays comfortably under these floodgates, while the opponent keels over and dies. If you have access to any of these cards, they generally insta-win you the game since they shut off almost every route of play.

While preferring to go first, this deck can still comfortably go second if forced to, since it features 12 hand traps. It can also play past interruption, since it has multiple methods to start off its gameplay.

I found it funny that almost nobody knows what the heck Generaiders and Windwitches do, and they end up underestimating the deck until it's too late. Before long, your opponent may find themself facing down Harr's omni-negate, Crystal Wing's monster negate, Dimension Shifter's banish, and lethal backrow like Judgment and Imperial Order!

Another bonus about this deck is that it functions nicely under Maxx "C," the undisputed king of Master Duel. This deck doesn't summon much, so the opponent doesn't have much incentive to use Maxx "C." This deck can even function under Summon Limit or Winda!

The only major problem about this deck is that it bricks HARD, since there are 6 "hard" bricks in the deck (5 Generaider bosses + Ice Bell) and 1 "soft" brick (Glass Bell). This weakness is avoided with Pot of Prosperity and Maxx "C" functioning as cards that will get you starters for the deck.

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: A deck that combines the swarming abilities of both the Zombie and the HERO archetypes to go to powerful Extra Deck boss monsters.
deck_description:
Welcome to my Zombie Heroes!

Do you enjoy flooding the board with powerful Extra Deck monsters while controling your opponent's every move? Then let me introduce you to this deck! Our main objective is to limit our opponents' moves as much as possible with cards like Zombie World, Masked HERO Dark Law, Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer and Doomking Balerdroch, while running them over with powerful bosses like Accesscode Talker and Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. The Zombie and HERO toolboxes will help us get there as fast as possible.

Your first turn priority goals are Zombie World , Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer and Doomking Balerdroch, in this order. A random Mask Change II can add Masked HERO Dark Law to the mix. All Normal Summons of this deck target to facilitate these goals. Be careful with Zombie Master though, although he can target a monster he just discarded to revive, he still needs a valid target in the GY to activate his effect.

- Zombie World is your number 1 priority. It shuts down any extra deck play that requires a specific type of materials, also your Super Polymerization can remove any 2 of your opponent's monsters for Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon and your Doomking Balerdroch can negate any moster effect on the field. Finally, you get the added enjoyment of floodgating and completely shutting down any random Floowandereeze you may encounter. If this ain't worth it, I don't know what is. ^_^
- Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer is your next goal. Not only is DPE a pretty solid turn 2 interruption, you'll also fill your GY with a Destiny HERO - Denier and a Destiny HERO - Malicious, just make sure to discard the Malicious in hand for the fusion, if you happened to draw one, you'll need the second one in deck to perform the Destiny combo that will give you a +3 next turn.
- Doomking Balerdroch is stupid strong with Zombie World. Any effect activation can be negated, and any (other) effect activation is a free banish for you.

If you made it to turn 3, you win.

Toss as many Mezuki you can to the GY as possible. Extra deck cards like Avendread Savior and Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal can facilitate this, although the first one will require your battle phase, but there are also 9 main deck cards that can send cards from deck to grave.

Use Destiny HERO - Malicious effect to banish him and summon another copy from the deck, then use Destiny HERO - Denier effect to summon himself from the GY and return the banished Malicious to deck. Link these two into anything (usually Avendread Savior), or if you have a Uni-Zombie on the field you can manipulate a level 4 into a level 6 and Xyz that with Malicious into Beatrice, Lady of the Eternal. In any case, make sure the Malicious on board ends up in the grave so that you can activate him again to summon back the one you've just returned to the deck. Don't hesitate to even use Beatrice as Link material after her effect, you can still revive her with a Mezuki, since she's a Zombie in this deck :D . You can see that ending up with either an Accesscode Talker or an I:P Masquerena boosted Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax is child's play at this point. Throwing a Zombie Master in between your combo, if you have the hand to discard for his cost, can even lead to an extra Borreload Savage Dragon or Baronne de Fleur on the field.

Some comments about certain card choices:
- 3 Maxx "C", 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 2 Called by the Grave and 3 Infinite Impermanence are kind of staples in any deck that wants to call herself competitive these days. It is what it is.
- A wild Mask Change II in your opening hand can change half your monsters into a Masked HERO Dark Law . Turn 1, this dude is solid on his own, but along with Zombie World  and DPE he's pretty much autowin. You can also use him for Beatrice material later, but keep in mind that the "Must be Special Summoned by "Mask Change"" part of his text won't let you revive him with a Mezuki , even if he's a Zombie in the GY.
- Triple Burst Dragon is here because I played a game against a Number 59: Crooked Cook deck at some point in my life and I vowed to myself that I will never play a deck without a hard counter for that dude.
- Ra'ten, the Heavenly General is an additional attribute for Accesscode Talker materials. Everything other Link Monster in the deck is dark, an additional removal never hurt anyone.
The new earth plunder ship is actually insane.  I've played plunder for a long time and this is my current list for random online stuff
N/A

A pretty basic deck idea utilizing a lot of the old-school monsters that attack directly.

Use Level Limit - Area B and Gravity Bind to prevent your opponent's monsters from attacking. Swords of Revealing Light or other attack-negating cards can be used to prevent Xyz and Link monsters from attacking your monsters.

Use equip cards like Mage Power (assuming you'll have cards like Level Limit - Area B and/or Gravity Bind in play) or other attack-boosting card effects to increase the damage that your monsters do when they attack. 

Notably missing are any kind of hand traps or effect-negating cards, which might leave you vulnerable.

The extra deck is mainly about summoning stronger monsters to attack over some of your opponent's monsters, deal some effect damage, special summon additional monsters, and/or protect your cards.

deck_excerpt: Their is more to this deck than it seems.
deck_description: Core idea to have Illusion of chaos in hand, use as vehicle for different DM fusions or summoning Slifer/Obelisk.

Mudora gains 200 ATK for each Fairy type monster in your graveyard, so the point is to try to get some Fairy monsters in the graveyard to buff Mudora and beat over some cards. Alternate options include summoning Vanity's Ruler to prevent special summons, or Guardian Angel Joan as a beat stick that can give you some extra life points in the process.

The Agent of Creation - Venus could be inserted into this deck to special summon three copies of Mystical Shine Ball and use those for Xyz summons. Detach them and get them in the GY while also getting to use the Xyz monster's effect(s).

Dark Hole could be used to get rid of your opponent's monsters while also getting more Fairies in the GY. Tuners and Synchros could also be a good way to get Fairies in the GY. Other cards like Exchange of the Spirit could be used to both get Fairies in the GY and mess with your opponent's GY/Deck strategies.

There are plenty of Fairy-type monsters and support cards that could work well, so try Mudora out with different Fairies as a fun gimmick.

deck_excerpt: Fortune Lady, Dogmatika, Shaddoll, Non-Meta Decks
deck_description:
The main objective of this deck is control. From my play testing it hasn't been hard getting cards in the grave for the primary target Winda. Getting both Winda and Every on the field plus some dogmatika pops has been moderately successful in the lower tiers.

The biggest issue I've found with the deck is that it's incredibly slow, which hinders it from competing with pretty much any competent/consistent deck unless their pilot is not experienced with their deck. Your biggest advantage is no one has any clue what you're doing and if one line (say your Fortune line) gets negated, you can usually go into your Shaddoll or Dogmatika lines after.

I believe adding the other Fortune Lady cards only makes this deck more bricky/inconsistent than it already is which this deck DOES NOT need, especially since they have incredibly niche applications that don't meaningfully progress your gameplan.

I'm posting this deck because I think it's as solved as it'll currently get but if someone comes along with innovations or if new cards enter play, I'd like to see where people can take my variant.

deck_excerpt: Give us more Toon support Konami
deck_description:
This Toon deck is based on the main deck almost exclusively. The extra deck is almost only to fuel spells and traps like Ghost Reaper and Dogmatika Punishment. I'll go over every card in the card in the deck, explain why it's there, and at the end explain some of the strengths, weaknesses, and strategies of the deck.

2x Toon Black Luster Soldier: This is the strongest monster in the deck, but you don't really want to draw it and rather summon it from deck off of Toon Page-Flip or Toon Dark Magician, so I only play two.

3x Toon Dark Magician: This card is an extremely good searcher for the deck, being able to search nearly two-thirds of the deck by itself. In most situations, this is the monster you want to see off of Toon Page-Flip.

2x Red-Eyes Toon Dragon: Once again, this is a card that is very good for the deck but you don't really want to draw it, getting it off of Page-Flip, Dark Magician, or Black Stone of Legend. This is the other prefered card to get off of Page-Flip.

1x Toon Cyber Dragon: This is only here in case you need another monster to select for Page-Flip, or if you're going second and want to make Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon with your opponents monster.

2x The Black Stone of Legend: I would recommend only playing as many of these as you play Red-Eyes. This can either get Red-Eyes, or if it would be more useful, get Linkuriboh.

2x Field Barrier: This is to protect Toon Kingdom from being destroyed. 

3x Comic Hand: One of the best cards in the deck, you can just take one of your opponents monsters and it can attack directly for no cost. The only downside is it's an equip spell, but that's not too bad of a downside.

3x Toon Kingdom: The absolute best card in the deck, this protects your Toons from destruction by battle and card effects. You need to have this on the field and be able to protect it.

1x Dark Ruler No More: In case you have to go second, you can use this to stop any negates to be able to set up your end board, and since you won't be doing any life points your first turn, not being able to deal life points doesn't affect the deck much.

1x Harpie's Feather Duster: Spell and Trap removal, which the deck desperately needs since almost none of the deck has any form of removal.

2x Pot of Prosparity: You can either run this or Extravagance, but I prefer Prosparity since you can choose what cards you banish and choose what card to get, but if you think drawing more is better go ahead.

1x Terraforming: Use this to search for Toon Kingdom.

3x Toon Bookmark: The best searcher in the deck, as you can search most of the deck with it and it acts as protection for Toon Kingdom in the graveyard.

1x Toon Rollback: Since the end board of TBLS, Red-Eyes, and Dark Magician is 100 lp off lethal, I run one of these to give that last push if needed.

3x Toon Table of Contents: Almost as good as Toon Bookmark, but without the protection and it can't search Comic Hand unfortunately. Usually I end up using this to search out Bookmark to get more protection for Toon Kingdom.

3x Toon Page-Flip: This is to search either TBLS, Red-Eyes, or Dark Magician. None of them are bad to get off of this, but it is definitely preferred to get Red-Eyes or Dark Magician than TBLS simply because usually with one of those two you can get TBLS on the field anyway.

3x Toon Terror: The only negate in the deck, which is pretty good but requires Toon World and a Toon monster which only happens most of the time.

2x Dogmatika Punishment: Basically free removal since we don't use the extra deck too much.

1x Metaverse: Just in case you can't get Toon Kingdom out on your turn, you can try and get it out on your opponents.

1x Toon Briefcase: This is a decent card that doesn't activate graveyard effects which is pretty good, but if you want you can run a third Punishment instead.

Dragon Master Knight, Flower Cardian Lightflare, Superdimensional Robot Galaxy Destroyer, and Five-Headed Link Dragon: These are for Dogmatika Punishment and that's it.

1x Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon: One of the only cards in the extra deck we actually use. If you don't run Toon Cyber Dragon don't run this, and vice versa.

2x Linkuriboh: The other card we actually use sometimes in the extra deck, this is only for if it would more useful to get this than Red-Eyes.

The rest of the extra deck: These are just here to be targets for Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries. You can change these out for other cards if you think they are more of an issue.

1x Blue-Eyes Toon Dragon: I don't know, I just think it's funny and it doesn't feel like a Toon deck to me without this guy being at least somewhere.

3x Dimension Shifter: This is good against a variety of decks, and is just a good card.

3x Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring: It's Ash. That's it.

3x Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries: An underrated handtrap in my opinion, this against a few decks can just shut them down depending what is in our extra deck.

1x Pot of Prosperity: In case you want one more, here it is.

2x Evenly Matched: In cases where we brick and can't do anything, this is a good card to make the opponent destroy almost all of their board.

2x Toon Briefcase: If you really like this card, you can use more if you want.

Now for the strengths and weaknesses of the deck:

Strengths: Many people don't know what this deck can do, and they will think it's an easy victory because Toons are widely regarded as very bad. This deck is very good at OTKing if you get the right board.

Weaknesses: This deck is kind of bricky, and the deck cannot stop Zeus. If the opponent can get Zeus on the field, your best bet is for you to side into Ghost Reaper and pray you draw it, because if you don't you almost always lose.

Tips: 1) Go first if you can. This deck is based OTKing, but since most Toons can't attack the turn they are summoned the first turn you can OTK is turn 3 if you go first. 2) Protect Toon Kingdom. Get as much protection as you can for it, because if you don't, you will just lose. The main way to do this is using Table of Contents -> Bookmark -> The card you need.

deck_description:
My take on the "Amazement" archetype.

It's a pretty standard build that seeks to control the board through the theme's very own "Amaze Attraction" trap cards and other really strong, high-impact trap cards. Like with all my other decks, the Side Deck is tailored to combat common threats at my Local OTS, so if you want to try out this deck, I suggest tweaking it so that it makes more sense for you.

Hello, this is the first deck I'm submitting ever, so I'm gonna try and explain what the idea behind its strategy is.

Hieratics:

-Monster gate is basically a hieratics card, using this is a bit risky if you run many handtraps but it gives you so much adavntage by using a hieratic as a targer it's a no brainer to use, then, you want to prey not to get an ash on field with its effect

-Creation is great to use to cheese out atum a second time, since you can use one atum to go into gaia, then overlay the other atum on top of gaia. 

-Convocation is hieratic's rota, with it you're mostly gonna add su, and if you're going second you might wanna consider tefnuit

-Tefnuit is hieratic's cyber dragon, it's great going second, but if you are first you are mostly gonna use him by discarding it some way

-Eset is just ok, if you have him first you might wanna summon it or just using it as discard fodder, main use of this card is to summon it via Atum

-Su is extremely great, you wanna ss him by tributing spheres, however you manage to get them onto the field (more on this later), and you always wanna have one or more in hand, he's used to summon atum 100% of the times

-Spheres is the first extra deck monster you wanna summon, I suggest summoning it using collapserpent and wyverbuster or seyfert: you use one of the babies to summon Striker, and add the other baby to hand to summon itself by banishing the other baby, and then use them both to go on spheres. After that, tribute the spheres to summon su from hand, and maybe another su of tefnuit from deck. Remember that sphere's effect only activates once, so it's no use getting him back on the field with darkness metal dragon

-Atum is great: the first time you are gonna use its effect for an easy darkness metal dragon, which will allow you to ss from grave su, then you either link  atum and dmd into romulus, or if you have creation you want to summon gaia to use creation and rank up into atum again. Second time you are gonna use its effect is gonna be to summon samsara dragon, then you get samsara in grave and use its eff to summon a lv6 by using the other su as tribute, this way you have two other lv6 to go on Beyond, another Atum, or Bounzer.

Byssted

The Bystial Lubellion 

-Lubellion is great, it's a Rota for byssted and can special summon himself from grave by tributing a dark dragon, which is of course going to be either a byssted or the labradorite, and when he hits the field, you are going to activate Branded beast, which we'll talk about in just a second

Bystial Saronir 

-Saronir is going to be a key component to the byssted end board, as all level 6 byssted you can summon him by banishing 1 light or darkness from either graveyard, if it's gonna be yours, I suggest striker dragon or maybe an atum, but anything is fine, then, you want saronir to go to grave, either by linking him away, or by summoning lubellion from grave, or by going into autm. Once he hits the field, you wanna send Branded regained (formally known as rebranded (which in my opinion sounded a lot better)). Having branded regained on grave is gonna be extremely great, you'll see why in just a moment.

Bystial Magnamhut 

-Magnamhut is great, if you can summon him, go for it, even during your opponent's turn, as he's gonna add you a dragon from deck or gy, this is extremely great to have as an effect as it may help you gain extra deck monsters for your next turn, or other byssteds to be used with the spell and traps

Bystial Druiswurm 

-Druiswurm is also great, you're going to summon him during your opponents turn mostly and you want to get him off of the field to pop 1 of your opponent's monsters, which is a really valuable effect

Branded Beast 

-Beast is the trap card, you wanna place this one on your field via Lubellion's effect, it's gonna be a form of removal via tribute, which is gonna trigger your druiswurm or hieratics, but also, it allows you to place branded regained on the field from grave, which is great

Branded Regained 

-Rebraned is the spell one, this has two effects that can be activated during your opponent's turn to give you advantage: first, if a monster is banished, it lets you add that monster to the deck and draw 1, basically another chaos space, and this effect is going to be activated whenever you summon a byssted during your opponent's turn, so mainly when you summon druiswurm. The second effect is going to trigger when you opponent summons, this is going to let you summon one byssted from grave, either druiswurm or magnamuth to setup a card for your next turn

Dragonlink package

Starliege Seyfert 

-Seyfert is really great, you wanna use it to search for a collapserpent or for a Saronir, with collapserpent you want to go into spheres to be tributed using su, and with saronir you want to setup the end byssted board, may have other uses but these ones are the main ones in my opinion.

Black Dragon Collapserpent 

White Dragon Wyverburster 

-The babies are extremely great at giving you spheres or romulus, in case you don't know how: summon one baby, link it away into striker, add the other one to you hand, banish the baby to summon the second one, link the second and striker into your link2 dragons. These bad boys are going to make your combo way easier.

Chaos Space 

-Chaos space is basically a spell version of seyfert, it's great + it lets you draw one

Dragon Ravine 

-Ravine is extremely good with this deck: you wanna use it to send samsara dragon and the guardragon one, or to send lubellion, I suggest samsara just because he's gonna be used to allow you to go into atum a second time with ease

Dragunity Knight - Romulus 

-Romulus: add ravine and maybe summon 1 from hand if you're really feeling it

Striker Dragon 

-Striker is just gonna be fodder to go into your link2

Guardragon Pisty 

-This one is a bit finnicky to use in this deck, but it can work: summon him in left zone, and then summon triple burst dragon in the extra zone afterwards, not the other way around, please. You can then use the effect to summon whatever you want to extend your plays, maybe an apollousa could be an idea idk I never know what's the right call with this situation so you might wanna try some stuff by yourself

Triple Burst Dragon 

-Trip is going to let you use pisty if you're feeling like it, summon pisty before this one please

Lv1 Dragons + labradorite

Samsara Dragon

-samsara is cute and really helpful, you wanna send him to grave via ravine, then trigger its effect to summon a level 6 from grave by tributing a hieratic on field, if you remember the combo is atum>dmd>su from grave> romulus with atum and dmd, so you're always gonna end up with a su or tefnuit to use as a tribute, and being tributed is gonna let you summon labradorite to go into atum a second time

World Chalice Guardragon 

-Guardragon is also very cute, and also likes to be on grave, you can send him via ravine (BUT remember that samsara has the priority), or you wanna summon him with the second atum's effect specifically, then you link him away and use its effect to bring labradorite on field once again, an extra body is always great

Labradorite Dragon 

-Lab you wanna use to summon the 2nd atum, or if you wanna hurt yourself and use the tzolkin variant of the deck you can summon him, otherwise, you summon him via guardragon to go into utopia or bounzer

Other extra deck

I:P Masquerena 

-Masq is gonna be used to summon knightmare or apollousa if you're playing her

Photon Strike Bounzer 

-Bounzer is a monster negate and a decent attacker, but remember that he negates monsters that are already on the field, go into this one at the end of your combo using labradorite and another lv6 but remember that he's not gonna be super useful

Number 39: Utopia Beyond 

-If you're going to attack for critical this one is decent, never use him if you go first though

Gaia Dragon, the Thunder Charger 

-Gaia is only useful if you have creation in hand, otherwise, consider using him as fodder for prosperity

Ultimaya Tzolkin + Void Ogre Dragon  + Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon  + Lost Wind 

ultimaya is pretty bad 90% of the time, but if you like suffering you can add him to your ed (not sure what to remove tho) and you wanna summon the two dragons, if you feel really cool you can set lost wind from grave during your opponent's turn.

Side deck+ cards to consider

Constellar Ptolemy M7 

-Ptolemy is one I forgot to add this one but is sometimes better than the other rank 6

Card Advance 

This one lets you tribute summon one extra time and also lets you setup your next draw, unfortunately you're almost never going to set the next card because you often wanna tribute hieratics that usually summon stuff from deck

Dragunity Arma Gram 

-Arma gram is a strong dude and a negate, you might wanna use him when going second by summoning him from grave

Amorphage Sloth + Zerozerock 

-If you manage to trigger sphere's during your opponent's turn this one is a neat floodgate but unfortunately is always gonna have 0 atk/def, so you might wanna add zerozerock idk your choice anyways this one is gonna be at the very least an annoyance to remove since your opponent is most likely gonna waste the battle phase

 

 

 

That's all goodye

While this deck is built around venom counters, it has several Reptile-based combos, too. Dear god, I am better with Magic: the Gathering decks. I haven't played this game in years!

Feedback is always welcome.

deck

#1 Scareclaw YugiTuber!

 

If your looking for a deck to go against the meta this is it! I've been playing scareclaw for 5 months now and have perfected this deck with many different versions that are just as good if not better. Check out my YT channel if you want to see me break down how to play the deck and I use it in every livestream as well where you can ask Q's real-time.

 

I have a playlist with nothing but epic Scareclaw content!

Deck is built for Master Duel forbidden & limited lists.

Going first, the primary idea is get Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights into play, put Rookie Warrior Lady in hand. If you already have Rookie Warrior Lady, put Immortal Phoenix Gearfried into your hand instead. Then, use Isolde to find Hero Kid. Use those to play Gouki The Powerload Ogre and pass

Cards not on Master Duel - Ashura King, Heroic Champion - Jarngreipr

Get Ameba and Griggle on the field, use any of Shien's Spy (to get the card back at the end of the turn), Mystic Box (to get rid of your opponent's monster), or Creature Swap (to get one of your opponent's monsters) and then inflict 2000 damage (Ameba) or gain 3000 life poins (Griggle). Geonator Transverser can also be used and offers some destruction prevention, but is more limited in where it can swap monsters.

Then, summoning The Agent of Judgment - Saturn and/or The Agent of Force - Mars will let them use their effects (assuming you still have the significant LP advantage) to deal more damage and/or beat over some of their monsters.

Kozaky can be set and then transferred to your opponent, flipped face up either by attacking into it or using Ceasefire, and then it will self-destruct; dealing your opponent 2500 damage.  

Messenger of Peace is mainly used to protect you from high ATK attacks. Lava Golem can be summoned to your opponent and cost them 1000 LP/turn while also getting rid of 2 of their monsters. Number 30: Acid Golem of Destruction functions in a similar way. Use Number 30: Acid Golem of Destruction for a couple of attacks and then transfer it to your opponent once it no longer has materials, which will inflict 2000 damage to your opponent each turn until they can get rid of it. You could also use Ring of Destruction (assuming you have more LP [from Griggle]) to inflict more damage. 

Other cards are either support, protection, or additional ways to inflict burn damage (like Grenosaurus).

deck_excerpt: Unleash the HERO of the Crystals.
deck_description:
A semi-control oriented Crystal Beast deck with a couple of power houses in the Extra Deck.

You can can control the board with "Rainbow Bridge of the Heart" and "Crystal Conclave", both of which are excellent for searching cards from the deck and allowing you to bounce opponents cards to help clear the way for your Crystal Beasts.

Rainbow Neos is the HERO which this deck needs and deserves, with the ability to clear the opponent's board in a single move, with non-targeted, non-destructive removal. 

You could also sacrifice a Crystal Beast monster to activate the "Ultimate Crystal Magic" Trap Card to summon the Rainbow Overdragon for a powerful beatstick with excellent removal.

Most of the Extra Deck is a small toolbox to help the Crystal Beast strategy and/or help close out games.

Go forth and make Jesse Anderson proud.

deck_excerpt: Hello people look at my deck
deck_description: Its Swordsoul. this is as budget as I can make it without cutting the main mechanics of the deck. Let me know if there are any changes i should make

The goal is to get into "Morphing Jar" as fast as possible. You can search it by "Gallant Granite" for which you need 2 level 4 monsters or by normalsummoning "Spirit of the fall winds", then you still need to make "Gallant Granite" to specialsummon "Morphing Jar". Funny enough, since "Cyber Jar" is legal, this deck became more consistent. If you have successfully set down "Morphing Jar", you need one opener like "Book of Taiyou" or "A/D Changer" or another 2 level 4 monsters to make "Photon Papilloperative" so you can flip up "Morphing Jar". Then you need cover cards like "Book of Moon", "Invoked Raidjin" or again 2 level 4 monsters to make "Wind-Up Zenmaister". You constantly flip up and down "Morphing Jar" to generate ressources. If your deck count goes lower than your opponents you need to use "needle worm" to mill your opponents deck. Although this build is very consistent, it has a hard time playing around handtraps, but it is possible to do so. Like you can dodge Impermanence with Book.

This is my personal Ritual build. After many different decks this is the list I liked best. Baroness is insane, can summon Iwato or Yata from deck, to either skill drain or Yata lock the opponent. This deck has caused many an opponent to rage quit, and it is rather good: the ability to play extra techs like Unicore and Chaos Max is very helpful, and using Transonic to summon either Shinobird from deck on their turn to either spin their backrow or monsters can be a game-clutcher.

This deck dosen't brick often, and just so you know Greatfly and Cross-Sheep are MVPs, though you won't usually use them because of the Impcantations, but still: Greatfly link climb has won me games and cross sheep has drawn me to victory.

Kaijus ARE SO GOOD in  this deck you've no idea; they're board breakers and ritual fodder, dosen't get much better then that.

There are many ways to play Ritual, but this is my personal way and one of the best.

deck_name: Plunder Patrollship Jord deck,[PHHY], Zalamander Catalyzer,[DABL-TCG]

deck_description: A deck where you can take advantage of your synergie between Thunder Dragons and Myutant effects.

Turn 1 usually goes with Argonaut + Toad but you need to have Dive in hand first

Turn 2 is up to you, either OTK with Accesscode or make opponent surrender with 3/4 negates

This deck was inspired by AVAULT's build on YouTube. Just made some minor tweaks to the main and side deck.

The idea here to turbo out Meteor Black Dragon with Fusion Party and just go for the OTK. Run (3) of each of the fusion materials as we'll want to see them as soon as possible. We also run (3) Double Coston to pay for Red-Eyes. This will be helpful if you need some extra attack for the OTK or if you get really unlucky and don't draw into Meteor Dragon. Sphere Kuriboh is here to prevent dead hands and provide some protection. 

As for spells, we'll run (2) Polymerization and (3) Summoner's Art. This pretty much gurantees we can perform the fusion on our first or second turn. If you want, you could probably even replace one of the Polys (or both?) with a Hammer Shot to help clear the board. I've rarely had to use an extra Poly as Fusion Party is just an incredibly powerful card for this deck.

For traps we run (2) Dust Tornado and (2) Red-Eyes Spirit. Dust Tornado to keep the backrow clear and Red-Eyes Spirit to get our fusion pieces back with ease for even more attack.

The extra deck willl just run (3) Meteor Black Dragon. A very classic and nostalgic card if you grew up on Forbidden Memories like I did. The side deck is kind of a toolbox to deal with whatever you need to in the current meta. Anyways, have fun with it!

deck_excerpt: I don’t have three Nova, don’t feel like buying two more, and this is still consistent and recursive.
deck_description:
Borreload Riot? Borrelcode? Sauravis? BLACK ROSE DRAGON!? This deck is built to consider every possible scenario.

 

Riot recurs from the grave to loop back as a one-card starter every turn AND negates a summon.

Borrelcode is a last ditch reset button--same with Black Rose.

Sauravis is a big body or a big hand trap. And who cares if your ritual monsters hit the grave? Drytron doesn't care.

Need an unbreakable board? Chaos MAX and Vanity's Ruler turn 1 is a pretty good start.

Need to negate? Go the Herald route.

Need something completely different? Go to the side deck and grab a kaiju, DRNM, fight Runick banishment with Rastaban, throw in a makeshift Scythe and N'Tss combo.

This isn't meta, but it's a toolbox in the purest sense of the word: prepare for anything...and it's a ton of fun since there are so many weird paths you can take. Borrelsword + Chaos MAX OTK? Sure. Unchained Abomination for no reason? Go for it. Draco, Quad, and Riot Dragon on the field for effect, backrow, and special summon hate PLUS 11k ATK? Go for it.

deck_excerpt: Search 6, Draw 5, and lock your opponent's board... With 1 Punk Ze Amin!
deck_description:
PUNK has been slaughtered by the banlist. Dying for the sins of the current meta decks - Tearlaments and Spright, PUNK lost two key combo cards - Halqifibrax and Chaos Ruler. Effectively cut off from most of it's combo lines, PUNK has been reduced to a shell of it's former self.

Losing its two MVPs, PUNK can only turn to incorporating other archetypes and enablers to pack a competitive punch, and I present to you - PUNK Reptile Lock.

After seeing an incredible combo video by /u/Armytile on Reddit, I was inspired to make my own tweaks and Youtube video featuring this strategy. 

PUNK Reptile seeks to perform a one sided "Mystic Mine" like lock on your opponent, while having enough resources afterward to OTK with a classic PUNK board.

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 

  • Seeking to turbo two level 8s on the board for Bishbaalkin, the PUNK cards in the Main Deck consist of 15 cards:

3 Emergency Teleport, 3 Ze Amin, 3 Ogre Dance, 3 Foxy Tune, 2 Deer Note and 1 Sharakusai. In the Extra deck, there are 2 Amazing Dragons and 1 Dragon Drive. I chose to not include the other PUNK cards like Madame Spider, Wa Gon or the PUNK S/T since they do not enable the main combo.

 

  • Forming the basis of the "Reptile Lock," the various Reptile cards from different archetypes in the Main Deck consist of 6 cards: 
1 Reptillianne Coatl, 1 Reptillianne Lamia, 1 Reptillianne Nyami, 1 Danger!? Tsuchinoko?, 1 Alien Kid, and 1 Evil Dragon Ananta.  In the Extra deck, there is 1 Alien Shocktrooper M-Frame, 1 Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll, 1 Reptilianne Echidna, 1 Reptilianne Hydra, and 1 Reptillianne Melusine. All the Main Deck Reptile cards are searchable through the regular combo as you make Reptilianne Echidna and Zer'oll. 

 

 

  • Generic Staple cards assist the Pure Punk strategy and consist of 19 cards.
The handtraps consist of 2 Ash Blossom, 1 Ghost Belle, 1 Ghost Ogre, 2 D.D. Crow, 1 Effect Veiler and 2 Infinite Impermanence. The blind second cards consist of 2 Dark Ruler No More and 2 Evenly Matched. Support cards consist of 1 Called by the Grave, 3 Crossout Designator and 2 Cosmic Cyclone. A particular part of the combo allows you to draw FIVE cards, and these cards are ratio'd so that they can be easily drawn into after the deck is thinned out through the regular combo. Lots of common staples are here as well for Crossout Designator targets. 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
Ideally, this deck likes to go first so it can make a board and you lockdown your opponent with a minimum of a 2 negate Apollousa, Alien Kid + Zer'oll forming the "Alien Lock," Melusine which destroys your opponent's ATK, + handtraps/backrow interruption you might've drawn into when you draw 5. 
 
This combo search 6, draw 5 and board lock combo is achieved with one card - PUNK Ze Amin. 
 

 

  1. Normal/Special summon Ze Amin. Activate Ze Amin’s effect to search for Foxy Tune.

  2. Activate Foxy Tune’s effect in hand and discard one card. Summon Sharakusai from deck.

  1. Activate Sharakusai’s effect to fuse Ze Amin + Sharakusai. Fusion summon Rising Carp.

  1. Tribute Rising Carp to summon another Ze Amin + Deer Note from deck. Synchro for Mathmech Magma. 

  2. Deer Note effect in GY to summon from GY Rising Carp. Synchro Rising Carp + Magma to summon Bishbaalkin. 

  3. Bishbaalkin effect to summon to both fields 5 tokens. 

  4. Link away Bishbaalkin + token for Reprodocus. 

  5. Reprodocus effect and declare change type. Declare type reptile. 

  6. Link away reptile token + regular token for Reptilliane Echidna. 

  7. Link away 2 last tokens for I:P Masquerena. 

  8. Link I:P Masquerena + Reprodocus for Apollousa. 

  9. Activate Reptilliane Echidna's effect to search for 5 reptile monsters from deck. Search for Coatl, Lamia, Nyami, Tsuchinoko, and Ananta. 

  10. Activate Coatl in hand to summon Coatl, Lamia and Nyami to field. 

  11. Link away Echidna + Nyami to summon Alien Shocktrooper M-Frame.

  12. Activate Shocktrooper's effect discarding Tsuchinoko. Put 3 Alien Counters on Apollousa. Tsuchinoko summons itself from the GY due to it's own effect.

  13. Link away Shocktrooper + Tsuchinoko for Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll. Zer'oll searches for Alien Kid on summon. 

  14. Summon Alien Kid from hand with Zer'oll's effect, removing Alien Counters from Apollousa. 

  15. Summon Nyami from GY with it's own effect. 

  16. Synchro away Nyami + Coatl for Hydra. Hydra effect on summon to draw 5 cards. 

  17. Synchro away Lamia + Hydra for Melusine. 

  18. You should have 6+ cards in hand, many of which are hand traps. Set cards on your field so you don't have to discard any. 

With this completed board, your opponent has to deal with a 2 monster negate Apollousa. Alien Kid + Zer'oll force your opponent's monsters in defense position and have their effects negated. Melusine turns your opponent's monsters ATK to 0 once per chain. You also should have many handtraps and backrow interruption, due to the draw 5 from Hydra after you thinned out your deck. 

A highly respectable board that originates from 1 card, even for today's meta - all accomplished without Halqifibrax and Chaos Ruler! 

 

GENERAL TIPS

 

  • If you have an extender like Emergency Teleport or Foxy Tune in hand as well as Ze Amin, try to bait out your opponent’s interruption by activating Ze Amin’s search effect. She is excellent hand trap bait. Summon Sharakusai from deck afterwards and proceed to full combo!
  • All that is needed is 1 Ze Amin to start the combo. There are 12 copies of Ze Amin in this deck - 3 Foxy Tune, 3 Ogre Dance, 3 Emergency Teleport and 3 Ze Amin herself. If you don't have Ze Amin in your starting hand, then you unfortunately bricked.  
  • This deck's main combo dies to almost every handtrap. This is why I've opted to maximize on Crossout Designator and Called by the Grave to protect your combo lines.
  • This deck loses hard to common floodgates like Gozen Match, Skill Drain and Mystic Mine. That is why 7 backrow removal cards are available.  
  • As incredible as this deck's uninterrupted first turn board is, it can still be cracked by S/T-based board breakers like Evenly Matched, Dark Ruler No More, Super Poly, etc. However, even after you get board wiped, this deck features ample follow-up with Ananta and PUNK monsters in hand/GY! 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

Again, shoutout to /u/Armytile on Reddit for labbing out this strategy  and inspiring me to make my guide featuring this strategy. 

After being devastated of the losses of Chaos Ruler and Halqifibrax for the sins of the meta, I've been searching far and wide for a competitive strategy that I can use PUNK in. PUNK Reptile offers some comfort, as the flashy SEARCH 6, DRAW 5 combo and BOARD LOCK bears some semblance of meta viability. The question is - is this fragile combo able to last in the brutally fast and ferocious competition of Tearlaments, Sprights, Mathmech and Exorsisters? Only practice, time and experience will tell. 

Hopefully PUNK gets more viable options in the future so I can start my Cyberpunk shenigans again - competitively. For now, we have this beautiful crazy combo to enjoy.

That’ll be all for now, GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: TeleDAD 60 Card Deck List & Combos October 2022
deck_description:
Feeling nostalgic? This old school deck has been updated for the October 2022 format! 

Why run 60 cards instead of 40 cards?

  • This is to minimize drawing into bricks such as PSY-Frame Driver, the second copy of Destiny HERO – Malicious, etc.

  • Having extra cards will help minimizing drawing into Dark Armed Dragon too early in the game.

  • Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights needs to send 4 equip cards with different names from the deck to the graveyard to combo off most of the time. By running extra cards, this will prevent drawing into the equip cards or too many of them. This will increase the likely hood that Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights’ effect will be live.

  • Staples like Forbidden Droplet and Infinite Impermanence can be ran. It’s nearly impossible to fit the essential cards and staples while keeping the deck size at 40 cards.

Combo One

Hand

  • A Hero Lives

Board

  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon (X2)

  • Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste

  • Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade (Set)

  • Armageddon Knight (Hand)

Notes

  • Two monster negates.

  • No effect damage. This is the perfect counter against Swordsoul. 

  • Armageddon Knight is in hand for a next turn play.

  • This is also a 2 card combo which can also be performed with Vision HERO Vyon, Armageddon Knight, or Dark Grepher, and any extender.

Steps

  1. Activate A Hero Lives, special summon Elemental HERO Stratos from the deck.

  2. Activate Elemental HERO Stratos, search Vision HERO Vyon.

  3. Normal summon Vision HERO Vyon, activate its effect to send Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from the deck to the graveyard.

  4. Activate Elemental HERO Shadow Mist, search Destiny HERO – Malicious

  5. Activate Vision HERO Vyon’s second effect, banish Elemental HERO Shadow Mist from the Graveyard, search Polymerization.

  6. Link summon into Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights (Elemental HERO Stratos + Vision HERO Vyon), then activate its effect to search Armageddon Knight.

  7. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights’ other effect, send 4 equip cards, including Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade, from the deck to the graveyard, then special summon Dark Grepher from the deck.

  8. Activate Dark Grepher, send Destiny HERO - Malicious from the hand to the graveyard, then send Plaguespreader Zombie from the deck to the graveyard.

  9. Activate Destiny HERO – Malicious, banish itself from the graveyard to special summon the second one from the deck.

  10. Activate Plaguespreader, place Armageddon Knight from the hand to the top of the deck, special summon itself from the graveyard.

  11. Synchro summon into Coral Dragon (Dark Grepher + Armageddon Knight).

  12. Synchro summon into Ultimaya Tzolkin (Coral Dragon + Destiny HERO – Malicious).

  13. Activate Coral Dragon, draw one card which will Armageddon Knight.

  14. Set Polymerization to activate Ultimaya Tzolkin. Synchro Summon into Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon.

  15. Activate Polymerization, fusion summon into Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste (Ultimaya Tzolkin + Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knight).

  16. Activate Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste, banish Ultimaya Tzolkin to gain its effect.

  17. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade, banish 2 warrior monsters from the graveyard, add this card from the graveyard to the hand.

  18. Set Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade to activate Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste. Synchro summon into the second copy of Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon.

Combo Two

Hand

  • Vision HERO Vyon

  • The Chaos Creator

Board

  • PSY-Framelord Lambda

  • Baronne de Fleur

  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon

  • Ultimaya Tzolkin

  • Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade (Equipped To Baroness de Fleur)

Notes

  • One omni-negate.

  • One monster negate.

  • Destroy one card on the field during your turn.

  • With Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade equip to Baronne de Fleur, its ATK becomes 3300.

Steps

  1. Normal summon Vision HERO Vyon. Activate its effect to send Destiny HERO – Malicious from the deck to the graveyard.

  2. Activate Destiny HERO – Malicious, banish itself from the graveyard to special summon the second one from the deck.

  3. Link summon into Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights (Vision HERO Vyon + Destiny HERO – Malicious). Activate its effect to add Any Warrior from the deck to the hand. If you just have these two cards in your hand, this will be shuffled back into the deck later on in the combo. You can shuffle another card back into the deck if it’s a brick in your hand.

  4. Activate Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights’ other effect to send 4 equip cards, including Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade, from the deck to the graveyard, then special summon Armageddon Knight from the deck.

  5. Activate Armageddon Knight, send Plaguespreader Zombie from the deck to the graveyard.

  6. Link summon PSY-Framelord Lambda (Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights + Armageddon Knight).

  7. Special summon The Chaos Creator by banishing Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights and Armageddon Knight from the graveyard.

  8. Activate The Chaos Creator, shuffle the banished Destiny HERO – Malicious back into the deck, put Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights back into the extra deck, and special summon Armageddon Knight from the banished zone.

  9. Activate Armageddon Knight, send the second Plaguespreader Zombie from the deck to the graveyard.

  10. Activate Plaguespreader Zombie, put the searched warrior from Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knight or a brick back on top of the deck if you have a third card in the hand, specials summon it from the graveyard.

  11. Synchro summon into Coral Dragon (Armageddon Knight + Plaguespreader Zombie).

  12. Activate Destiny HERO – Malicious, banish itself from the graveyard, special summon the previously banished copy from the deck.

  13. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade, banish 2 warrior monsters, add this card from the graveyard to the hand.

  14. Activate the second Plaguespreader Zombie, place Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade on top of the deck.

  15. Synchro summon into Ultimaya Tzolkin (Coral Dragon + Destiny HERO – Malicious).

  16. Activate Coral Dragon to draw one card which will be Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade.

  17. Set Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade from the hand to activate Ultimaya Tzolkin. Synchro summon into Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon

  18. Synchro summon into Baronne de Fleur (The Chaos Creator + Plaguespreader Zombie).

  19. Activate Divine Sword – Phoenix Blade and equip to Baronne de Fleur to gain 300 ATK.

deck_excerpt: An Unchained deck with an Evil Eye engine.
deck_description:
This is a going second Unchained deck using Serziel for additional interruption, recursion and (potentially) as a late game combo starter.

The main combo goes as follows:

1. Bait out an Ash Blossom using Terraforming/Evil Eye Domain.

2. Set any Unchained spell/trap. Destroy it with Aruha or Rakea.

3. Special summon Sarama from the deck. Use their effect to set your spell/trap onto the field and destroy your other Unchained monster.

4. Special summon Abominable Unchained Soul or Unchained Soul of Disaster from the deck. Go into Unchained Soul of Rage or any other available Fiend Link monster.

5. If you have your normal summon left, use it to summon Serziel and equip it with Evil Eye of Selene.

This does unfortunately leave you open for Nibiru (5 summons). If you want to play it safe and not risk having your field tributed, you can skip either step 3 or 5. If you think your opponent has a negate or interruption available, think about skipping step 3.

The side deck mostly consists of cards you can consider adding to your deck. If you know you are going first, it might be a good idea to take out DRNM for Infinite Impermenance or Evil Eye Retribution. If you have Pot of Prosperity, then you can also replace Pot of Extravagance with it to avoid unlucky banishes. The number of Torrential Tributes is up to preference.

Thank you for reading.

deck_excerpt: Use P.U.N.K. cards to turbo out Utopic Draco Future and Psychic End Punisher!
deck_description:
P.U.N.K. got hit pretty hard on the recent banlist, but this list lets them extend further and play a slower game if need be. You could remove the main-deck Ghostrick monsters from this list, but I wanted to challenge myself and see if I could build a list that uses them effectively. The endboard we are looking to make is Psychic End Punisher, Utopic Draco Future, and a set Ghostrick Renovation with a Ghostrick Mansion in our field zone, letting us activate Necrovalley on the opponent's turn. This isn't a final list, just a proof-of-concept that I hope others will take and run with to better optimize the build. I'll be going over what the archetypes do together, the card choices, and a few combos for the deck down below.

 

P.U.N.K. needs little introduction, they're an incredible synchro engine that can turbo-out Lv and Rank 8's, as well as Lv 3 mons. We use the Lv 3 summoning capabilities to make Alucard, which lets us extend into UDF while searching out other pieces of the Ghostrick toolbox. We lean heaviliy on the P.U.N.K. engine, so we are running a pretty full package. The Ghostricks in the deck are for turn 2 and later, letting us build advantage in a longer game, and helping us to survive if our combo gets stopped. The Lv 1's are here to protect our lifepoints and let us live for another turn should our board get broken, the Lv 2's are great at halting the opponent's momentum, and Jianshi is a good searcher. We are only running one Scare, as it is searchable and our turn 1 play doesn't involve setting mons, and we run Shot at 2 due to it's versatility and ability to extend our plays and provide follow-up on future turns.

 

Out basic lines of play all start with a P.U.N.K. starter (Ze Amin, Foxy Tune, Ogre Dance, Emergency Teleport, or Sharakusai with another P.U.N.K. in hand). Our goal is to get Ze Amin on the field, search Foxy Tune / any other starter, then combo to the best of our ability. If we normal Ze Amin and get negated, but have another starter in hand (E-Tele, Foxy), we can summon another Lv 3 and make Alucard, then follow the Ghostrick line into UDF, or we can extend further by summoning Sharakusai, fusion-summoning Rising Carp, using Carp to summon a Lv 3 and a Deer Note, make JAM Dragon Drive adn search our remaining Lv 3, summon back a Lv 3 / Lv 8 off of Deer note, and make either Psychic End Punisher or UDF. An ideal hand is Ze Amin, an extender, and another P.U.N.K. in hand. We summon Ze Amin, search Foxy / Ze Amin (if we already have Foxy), then special out Sharakusai. Fuse Ze Amin with the other P.U.N.K. in hand to make Rising Carp, tribute Carp to summon Wa Gon and Deer Note. Use Wa Gon to search the field spell and activate it, then make JAM Dragon Drive, searching Madame Spider and summoning back Sharakusai, and drawing a card off of the field spell. Special Madame Spider with the field spell, then search a trap, drawing another card. Make Psychic End Punisher, then overlay for Alucard, overlaying him for Angel of Mischief. Detatch Alucard to search Shot / Mansion / Renovation, depending on what your hand looks like. Summon back Alucard with Shot, overlay for another Angel, then detatch again to search another card, adding Shot back from GY with Alucard's effect. Overlay for Utopic Future, then for Utopic Draco Future. If we had Shot / Mansion / Renovation in hand at the start of the combo, we can also end on a set Renovation with Mansion active, swapping Mansion out for Necrovalley on the opponent's turn.

 

I hope this list has inspired you to make your own take on Ghostricks! Hopefully this has been a fun read, and an interesting build! Thank you for reading this, and I hope you have a great day!
